10. Contingency Planning and Resilience

Source: NIST SP 800-34r1 – Contingency Planning Guide for Federal Information Systems

Background information and terminology

Resilience

Resilience is the ability to quickly adapt and recover from any known or unknown environmental changes. The goal of a resilient organization is to continue mission-essential functions at all times during any type of disruption. Contingency planning is used to develop resilience and to protect the CIA (Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability).

  • According to NIST: Contingency planning is not a process, but rather an end-state for organizations
  • Environmental change can be:
    • Gradual changes (such as economic, technological, or mission changes)
    • Sudden changes (such as disaster events)

Business Continuity

Business continuity is the ability to maintain essential functions during and after a disaster has occurred. This means that essential business and mission functions continue to operate, and systems recover with as little downtime as possible.
Business continuity refers to plans for staying operational during a disruption by using risk management processes. Business continuity applies to all business functions and processes and is not limited to IT systems.

Business continuity planning relies on:

  • Business Impact Analysis (BIA)
    • reports that inform an organization of the most crucial functions and systems to prioritize in a business continuity plan
    • NIST recommends using FIPS 199 Impact Level standards to develop recovery strategies
  • Risk Assessment (RA)
    • Used to identify potential hazards to an organization

Business continuity management is an ongoing and evolving process to maintain resilience. Typical activities include:

  • Training Exercises
  • Communicating plans, and dissipating information
    • So that the employees and affected parties are aware and know what to do in case of a disaster
  • Business Continuity testing
    • do our recovery systems work?
  • Updating the business continuity plan


Source: https://www.ready.gov/business-continuity-plan

Disaster Recovery (DR)

DR is a subset of business Continuity Planning and is mainly focused on a specific information system (such as an IT system or service). The goal is to maintain the required CIA of a system in case of any disruptions. DR plans are also included in "Incident response" procedures and "Incident Response management" plans.

Types of Plans

Please see NIST SP 800-34r1 – Contingency Planning Guide for Federal Information Systems Chapter 2 for more information

  • Business Continuity Plan (BCP)
  • Continuity of Operations (COOP) Plan
  • Crisis Communications Plan
  • Critical Infrastructure Protection (CIP) Plan
  • Cyber Incident Response Plan
  • Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)
  • Information System Contingency Plan (ISCP)
  • Occupant Emergency Plan (OEP)

DR from IT Systems Perspective

Recover Objectives and Requirements

It would be nice to implement the absolute highest level of resiliency for all systems. Systems that have nearly 100% guaranteed uptime (availability) with nearly 100% integrity exist, however, those systems are usually very costly. As an IT professional, you will be expected to be able to "right-size" solutions for optimum performance and cost. Therefore, the first step in determining the correct solution for DR of an IT system is to establish organizational requirements. Here are some objectives that you will need to establish when designing a system:

  • RPO (Recover Point Objective):
    • Means to what point (how far back in time) to recover It indicates the maximum acceptable amount of data loss.
  • RTO (Recovery Time Objective):
    • Means how much time it takes to come back to full functionality from the time disaster struck. It indicates your acceptable downtime.
  • MTD (Maximum Tolerable Downtime):
    • The maximum amount of downtime before the impact on business or mission is too severe and intolerable.

Once you know what your design objectives are, then you can choose appropriate solutions to ensure those outcomes.

Disaster Recovery Patterns

Here are typical design patterns to meet recovery objectives while optimizing for costs:

  • Backup and Restore
  • Pilot Light (active-light out)
  • Warm-Standby (active-standby)
  • Multi-site (active-active)

Backup and Restore

The most basic requirement of any IT system is having backup and restore. The process is to make copies of the information to be protected at regular or predefined intervals and store them in a different secure medium or location. The backup copies can be in the form of local storage, external storage media, shared storage (network, NAS, SAN, Cloud), or offsite storage (when the backups are located in a different physical location).

The RPO determines the required frequency of the backups, while the RTO determines the required speed of restoration of data. The speed of restoration also determines the backup technology to use and how far away the backup can be from the source.

Backup and restore can be very cost-effective, and many businesses may be required by law to maintain information in archives for extended periods of time (for example in Canada businesses are required to keep their tax filing documents for up to 7 years). Additionally, backups can be designed to be multi-tiered, for example, "hot" backup copies can be used for sharing information between systems, while snapshots preserve the history of modifications, and "cold" backups can be periodically extracted from the "hot" source, and "archive" backups also periodically sourced from "cold" one. These processes may easily integrate into existing functions and designs of an IT system, further improving cost-effectiveness.

Cold Site (NIST terminology)

NIST defines a cold site as a designated physical building or location with basic infrastructure in place (for example electricity, communications, cooling etc.), but does not host any equipment. The idea is in case of a disaster (natural disaster or war) the site can be quickly occupied with equipment and staff ready to move in. These sites are provisioned for large-scale disasters such as earthquakes, volcanic eruptions, or nuclear attacks.

Pilot Light

Placing a bare minimum infrastructure in place to facilitate launching and "igniting" full infrastructure for services and processes when needed. An example can be having physical hardware in place, but powered off, and minimum required network gear up and running. In virtual environments or cloud deployments, this can take the form of automated scripts ready to be executed to implement the required system when needed.

In this case, RPO typically determines the resources and technologies needed for data replication, since usually bringing the required data and replication of data requires some constantly running systems. RTO determines how much resources are running as the pilot light. It may take minutes to hours to initialize all required servers and networks and for the information system to be able to start responding to and processing requests.

Example of a pilot-light implementation in AWS.

Warm Standby

Warm-standby is a duplicate set of systems which are not processing any information but are standing by for when they are needed. A worm-standby deployment can recover faster than a pilot-light deployment (often in seconds, or in some cases instant) due to the fact that all systems are pre-initialized and ready. Many hardware devices such as larger networking switches and blade server enclosures may contain redundant hardware on standby to take over functions in case the active hardware components fail.

In this pattern, the RPO determines the required data synchronization between the active and standby systems, and RTO determines the scale of the standby system, and supporting architecture. Supporting architecture requires technologies and systems to detect failure of the active systems and to re-route requests to the standby system in a timely fashion (to meet the RTO).

The following images are examples of such implementations in hardware.

HPE C7000 blade enclosure (can host up to 16 blade servers, and contains up to 8 (4+4) network or fibre channel switches). It features active-active fans and power supplies, and possibly switches depending on configuration, and active-standby "Onboard Administrators" which provides monitoring and managing control over the enclosure.

A Cisco switch which features active-standby management controller modules (in light blue slots).

Multi-site (Active-Active)

Milti-site deployments are usually the default deployment pattern for any mission-critical scenarios. It involves having redundant equipment running and processing information at the same time. The redundant systems share the workload but can handle the entire workload in case any peers experience failure or disruption. The sites can be at the same physical location or building, or extend to different geographic areas. Some system deployments mandate global deployments on different continents. An example of such deployment is global payment processors that deploy mainframes in clusters across multiple continents to guarantee uptime and transaction integrity, even under the most severe circumstances.

RPO is fully determined based on data and workload replication across the sites. RTO can be 0 (zero) with no downtime. In most cases, recovery is unnoticeable to clients.

DR Consideration

  • On-prem vs cloud
    • costs
    • Information security requirements
    • level of control over systems and information
    • Vendor-specific services and vendor lock-in
    • Skills
  • Response Management and Automation
    • Automation saves time! systems may respond faster than people
    • Automatic testing and patching
    • Automation requires upfront investment but pays off in the long run
    • Automation requires knowledge, skill, and proper documentation
      • how to avoid: "Joe left the company 6 months ago, nobody knows how this thing works"
  • Organizational culture
    • framework and regulation compliance requirements
    • IT budget
      • budget for procuring and maintaining equipment and systems
      • budget for retaining skills and talent for operation and maintenance
    • Outsourcing
      • Outsourcing skills
      • Outsourcing risks
      • Example: paying for and signing SLA (Service level agreements) with suppliers and vendors for a guaranteed level of response and service
